          "body": "The chapter's theological climax is 15:14: 'The Spirit of the LORD came upon him mightily so that the ropes that were on his arms were as flax that is burned with fire.' This is the same formula used at 13:25, 14:6, and 14:19 — the Spirit's empowerment is sovereign, recurring, and not contingent on Samson's moral worthiness in any given moment. What follows is the most dramatic single feat in the Samson cycle: one man kills a thousand warriors with the fresh jawbone of a donkey. The weapon itself is theologically loaded — a donkey was a ritually unclean animal under the Levitical code (Leviticus 11:26), and a jawbone is the most discardable part. Yet God uses this instrument to accomplish what no army of Judah would attempt. The point is not the weapon but the Wielder behind it. Samson's victory poem (15:16) celebrates the jawbone, not the Spirit; he names the place after the jawbone (Ramath-lehi, 15:17). God's place-name will wait for the spring (En-hakkore, 15:19) — where Samson finally stops taking credit and starts asking for help."
