        "number": 1,
        "title": "Domestic grievance becomes holy war — the self-justifying logic of retaliation",
        "range": "15:1-8",
        "excerpt": "Samson then said to them, 'This time I shall be blameless in regard to the Philistines when I do them harm.'",
        "body": "The chapter opens in domestic register — Samson arrives at his estranged wife's home with a young goat, intending reconciliation. The gesture is culturally appropriate: a gift animal signals goodwill. But he has been preempted; his wife has been given to his wedding companion (14:20), and her father now offers the younger sister as a substitute. Samson's response is not grief but legalism: 'This time I shall be blameless' (*naqah*, to be innocent, to be acquitted). He is constructing a moral framework in which his impending violence is justified by prior injury. The Hebrew *naqah* carries a forensic sense — Samson is declaring himself legally clean before he acts. This is not covenant warfare; there is no divine command, no prophetic word, no inquiry of the LORD. It is a personal grievance elevated to a just cause by self-declaration.\n\nThe fox-fire assault that follows (15:4–5) is staggering in its logistical scale — three hundred foxes caught, paired tail-to-tail, each pair fitted with a torch, and then released into the standing grain at harvest time. The harvest timing (15:1) is not incidental; wheat harvest was the most economically vulnerable moment for an agrarian society. The damage is comprehensive: shocks, standing grain, vineyards, and olive groves — the full agricultural economy of the region destroyed in one act. The Philistines are not wrong when they trace the act back to Samson (15:6); he has used a personal grievance to inflict economic warfare on an entire population.\n\nThe retaliatory chain then tightens with terrible efficiency: the Philistines burn Samson's wife and father-in-law (15:6), the very people Samson had used as his justification. Samson then strikes 'a great slaughter' (*makkah gedolah*, 15:8) — an undifferentiated military assault — before retreating to the rock of Etam. The opening eight verses of the chapter present a closed loop: every act of violence produces the next one, and the innocent — Samson's wife, her family, unnamed Philistine farmers — bear the heaviest costs of a quarrel not of their making.\n\nThe theological problem this raises is not peripheral. Deuteronomy 32:35 reserves vengeance (*naqam*) to God alone: 'Vengeance is Mine, and retribution.' Romans 12:19 will later ground this same text in the new covenant ethic. Samson's claim to blamelessness and his exercise of personal vengeance are not condemned explicitly by the narrator — but the Deuteronomistic framework of Judges makes the implicit judgment available to any reader who knows the Torah. The judge acts where only God has the standing to act.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Naqah* (blameless, 15:3) — the Niphal stem carries the sense of being absolved, acquitted, held guiltless; it is a courtroom term. *Naqam* (vengeance, 15:7) — the verbal noun form reserved in Deuteronomy for divine retribution; Samson's use of it is a usurpation of divine prerogative, whether he knows it or not. *Makkah gedolah* (great slaughter, 15:8) — a stock phrase for major military engagement; the same expression used of divinely commanded victories in Joshua and Samuel."
