        "excerpt": "Do you not know that the Philistines are rulers over us? What then is this that you have done to us?",
        "body": "The Philistine response to Samson's great slaughter is not to pursue him directly but to invade the territory of Judah — spreading out at Lehi (15:9). The strategic logic is sound: Judah has no stomach for resistance, as subsequent events demonstrate. When the men of Judah ask why the Philistines have come, the answer is precise: 'We have come up to bind Samson in order to do to him as he did to us' (15:10). The Philistines, remarkably, do not ask Judah to fight Samson — only to deliver him. And Judah, with almost no deliberation, agrees.\n\nThree thousand men of Judah descend to the rock of Etam to confront one man. The number is ludicrous — and intentionally so. The narrator wants the reader to feel the absurdity: Israel's largest tribe sends a military force sufficient to defeat a Philistine garrison to arrest their own judge. Their rebuke to Samson is morally inverted — 'What is this that you have done to us?' (15:11). The 'us' is telling: Judah has so thoroughly identified its interests with Philistine stability that Samson's resistance registers as aggression against Israel, not against the enemy. The oppressed have become the enforcers of their own oppression.\n\nSamson's response is measured: 'As they did to me, so I have done to them' (15:11). He makes no appeal to divine commission, no claim of prophetic mandate. He defends himself on the same retaliatory logic the Philistines used — which is precisely the problem. Neither Samson nor Judah is operating from covenant categories. Samson agrees to be bound and handed over on one condition: Judah must swear not to kill him themselves. The negotiation is oddly trusting — Samson allows himself to be bound with two new ropes and led up from the rock. He appears to trust that God will act, though he does not say so. This is, perhaps, the most theologically honest moment in the chapter's first half: Samson, unable to defend his actions covenantally, submits to a process he expects God to interrupt.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mashal* (rule/ruler, 15:11) — to have dominion, to govern; the same word used for legitimate royal authority. Judah applies the language of legitimate sovereignty to Philistine occupation — a profound theological error. *Shava* (swear, 15:12) — to take an oath; Samson requires a sworn guarantee, the most binding form of commitment in the ancient Near East. *Asar* (bind, 15:12–13) — the root occurs four times in four verses, insisting on the irony: Israel is binding the judge God has raised to bind the oppressor."
